uments.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>How the test works</h2>\n\n<p>You’ll be asked 100 questions in total. There are 25 questions in each of these 4 categories:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>driving practices and procedures, road and traffic signs, and motorway driving</li>\n  <li>driver attitude, the law, and environmental issues</li>\n  <li>vehicle dynamics and handling, and accident procedures</li>\n  <li>instructional coaching techniques, and hazard perception</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>How the scoring works</h2>\n\n<p>To pass the test you must get both:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>an overall score of at least 85 out of 100</li>\n  <li>at least 20 out of 25 in each of the 4 categories</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>You’ll fail if you get an overall mark of 85 or higher, but don’t score high enough in each category.</p>\n</div>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/become-a-fleet-driver-trainer/booking-the-practical-tests","slug":"booking-the-practical-tests","order":5,"title":"Booking the practical tests","body":"<p>There are 3 ways you can book and arrange the driving ability and instructional ability practical tests. </p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You’ll get an application form to book them when you pass the theory test.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Option 1 - arrange each separately</h2>\n\n<p>You can arrange both tests separately, and pay for them separately. </p>\n\n<h2>Option 2 - consecutive tests</h2>\n\n<p>You can pay for both tests at the same time, and book for the instructional ability test to take place straight after the driving ability test.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>You can’t take the instructional ability test if you fail the driving ability test - you’ll lose the fee you paid for the instructional ability test.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Option 3 - progressive tests</h2>\n\n<p>You can pay for both tests at the same time, but book for the instructional ability test to be at least 1 day after the driving ability test. </p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You can retake the driving ability test instead of taking the instructional ability test if you fail it.</p>\n</div>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/become-a-fleet-driver-trainer/taking-the-driving-ability-test","slug":"taking-the-driving-ability-test","order":6,"title":"Taking the driving ability test","body":"<p>The driving ability test includes:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>an eyesight test</li>\n  <li>a test of your driving ability</li>\n  <li>giving a descriptive talk-through commentary while driving</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The test lasts around 1 hour and costs £134.40.</p>\n\n<h2>What to bring to your test</h2>\n\n<p>On the day, you&rsquo;ll need to bring:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>both parts of your driving licence - the photocard and the paper counterpart</li>\n  <li>your approved driving instructor (<abbr title=\"Approved driving instructor\">ADI</abbr>) registration certificate</li>\n  <li>the pass letter from the theory test</li>\n  <li>a suitable car</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You must take your signed driving licence and a valid passport if you have an old-style paper licence.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Rules for the car you use</h2>\n\n<p>The car you use for the driving ability test must meet all the <a href=\"/adi-part-2-test/rules-for-the-car-you-use\" title=\"Rules for the car you use for the ADI part 2 test\">rules for the <abbr title=\"Approved driving instructor\">ADI</abbr> part 2 test</a>.</p>\n\n<h2>The eyesight test</h2>\n\n<p>You’ll have to read a number plate from a distance of:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>26.5 metres for vehicles with a new-style number plate</li>\n  <li>27.5 metres for vehicles with an old-style number plate</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>New-style number plates start with two letters followed by two numbers, eg AB51 ABC.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>You must use glasses or contact lenses during the whole test if you need them to read the number plate.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>You’ll fail the test if you don’t pass the eyesight test.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>The driving ability part</h2>\n\n<p>You’ll drive in varying road and traffic conditions, including motorways or dual carriageways where possible.</p>\n\n<p>You&rsquo;ll have to do 1 reversing exercise that the examiner chooses at random.</p>\n\n<p>You must prove to the examiner that you can move off safely and smoothly:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>uphill</li>\n  <li>downhill</li>\n  <li>ahead normally</li>\n  <li>at an angle</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You’ll need to give a descriptive talk-through commentary while driving for at least 10 minutes.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>Independent driving</h3>\n\n<p>You’ll have to drive without turn-by-turn directions from the examiner for around 10 minutes. You’ll have to follow either:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>traffic signs</li>\n  <li>a series of directions given to you before you set off</li>\n  <li>a combination of both</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>The examiner’s supervisor</h2>\n\n<p>The examiner’s supervisor may come along as well. They will be watching the examiner’s performance and won’t have a say in how you’re tested or in your result.</p>\n\n<h2>Your test result</h2>\n\n<p>There are 3 types of faults that can be marked:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>a dangerous fault - involves actual danger to you, the examiner, the public or property</li>\n  <li>a serious fault - could potentially be dangerous</li>\n  <li>a driving fault - not potentially dangerous, but if you make the same fault throughout your test it could become a serious fault</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Pass mark</h3>\n\n<p>You’ll pass the test if you make:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>no more than 4 driving faults</li>\n  <li>no serious or dangerous faults</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Failing the test</h3>\n\n<p>You&rsquo;ll be given a brief explanation of the faults you made if you don&rsquo;t pass the test. You&rsquo;ll also be given a form so you can apply to retake the test.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>You get 3 attempts at the test. You must wait 1 year before sending a new application to start the process again if you use up all your attempts.</p>\n</div>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/become-a-fleet-driver-trainer/taking-the-ability-to-instruct-test","slug":"taking-the-ability-to-instruct-test","order":7,"title":"Taking the ability to instruct test","body":"<p>The instructional ability test assesses how well you can identify and prioritise risk areas in a driver&rsquo;s driving.</p>\n\n<p>The test lasts around 1 hour and costs £134.40.</p>\n\n<h2>What to bring to your test</h2>\n\n<p>On the day, you’ll need to bring:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>both parts of your driving licence - the photocard and the paper counterpart</li>\n  <li>your approved driving instructor (ADI) registration certificate</li>\n  <li>the pass letter from the driving ability test</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You must take your signed driving licence and a valid passport if you have an old-style paper licence.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Rules for the car you use</h2>\n\n<p>The car you use for the driving ability test must meet all the <a href=\"/adi-part-2-test/rules-for-the-car-you-use\" title=\"Rules for the car you use for the ADI part 2 test\">rules for the ADI part 2 test</a>.</p>\n\n<h2>How the test works</h2>\n\n<p>The examiner will play the role of a company vehicle driver with various driving strengths and weaknesses. They will play only play 1 of the following roles:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>experienced car driver</li>\n  <li>inexperienced car driver</li>\n  <li>experienced van driver</li>\n  <li>inexperienced van driver</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You&rsquo;ll need to prove you can reduce their risks by using appropriate coaching methods. You&rsquo;ll have to give a risk profile at the end of the session.</p>\n\n<h2>The examiner’s supervisor</h2>\n\n<p>The examiner’s supervisor may come along as well. They will be watching the examiner’s performance and won’t have a say in how you’re tested or in your result.</p>\n\n<h2>Your test result</h2>\n\n<p>You&rsquo;ll get your result, a copy of the marking sheet and a short debrief from the examiner at the end of your test.</p>\n\n<p>You&rsquo;ll get a letter of confirmation if you pass. This includes the declaration you must complete send to the Driving Standards Agency before your certificate is sent to you.</p>\n\n<p>You&rsquo;ll get an application form to apply to retake the test if you don&rsquo;t pass.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>You get 3 attempts at the test. You must wait 1 year before sending a new application to start the process again if you use up all your attempts.</p>\n</div>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/become-a-fleet-driver-trainer/managing-your-registration","slug":"managing-your-registration","order":8,"title":"Managing your registration","body":"<p>Your registration will last for 4 years from when you join the register. </p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>You’re responsible for remembering when your registration runs out and renewing it.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>To renew your registration, download the application form and send it to the Driving Standards Agency (<abbr title=\"Driving Standards Agency\">DSA</abbr>) with the fee of £120 and a passport-syle photo.</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://assets.dft.gov.uk/dsa-bl/dsa-fleet-driver-trainer-renewal-application.pdf\" title=\"Download 'Application to renew fleet driver trainer registration' (PDF, 1.4MB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Application to renew fleet driver trainer registration’ (PDF, 1.4MB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"address\"><div class=\"adr org fn\"><p>\n\n\n<br />Register of Fleet Driver Trainers\n<br />Driving Standards Agency\n<br />The Axis Building\n<br />112 Upper Parliament Street\n<br />Nottingham\n<br />NG1 6LP\n<br 