100 questions in total. There are 25 questions in 4 categories. To pass the multiple-choice part you must get both:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>an overall score of at least 85 out of 100</li>\n  <li>at least 20 out of 25 in each of the 4 categories</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>You will fail if you get an overall mark of 85 or higher, but don’t score high enough in each category.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Hazard perception</h2>\n\n<p>You’ll then be shown 14 clips that feature every day road scenes. There will be:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>one developing hazard in 13 clips</li>\n  <li>2 developing hazards in one clip</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>A developing hazard is something that may cause you to take some action, such as changing speed or direction.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>You can get up to 5 points for each clip. The earlier you notice a developing hazard and make a response, the higher you score. You need to score at least 57 points out of 75 to pass this part.</p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/become-an-lgv-driving-instructor/taking-the-driving-ability-test","slug":"taking-the-driving-ability-test","order":6,"title":"Taking the driving ability test","body":"<p>To book the driving ability test, use the application form you’re given when you pass the theory test.</p>\n\n<p>The test lasts around 1 hour and 30 minutes. It costs £142.80.</p>\n\n<h2>What to bring to your test</h2>\n\n<p>You must bring:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>your valid Great Britain or Northern Ireland driving licence</li>\n  <li>a suitable vehicle</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You need to bring both parts of your driving licence - the photocard and the paper counterpart.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You must take your signed driving licence and a valid passport if you have an old-style paper licence.</p>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>Your test won’t go ahead and you’ll lose your fee if you don’t bring the right documents and a suitable vehicle.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Rules for the vehicle you use</h2>\n\n<p>You must bring a large goods vehicle that:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>is roadworthy and legal</li>\n  <li>is a category C1, C1+E, C or C+E vehicle (depending on the instructor certificate you want)</li>\n  <li>has normal performance for its type</li>\n  <li>is not carrying any goods or burden</li>\n  <li>is a right-hand drive</li>\n  <li>has a seat for a forward-facing passenger</li>\n  <li>has seatbelts fitted for the examiner&rsquo;s use</li>\n  <li>has external nearside and offside mirrors for use by the examiner during the test</li>\n  <li>does not display &lsquo;L&rsquo; plates during the test</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>How the test works</h2>\n\n<p>You’ll drive in varying road and traffic conditions, including motorways or dual carriageways where possible.</p>\n\n<p>You must prove to the examiner that you can move off safely and smoothly:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>uphill</li>\n  <li>downhill</li>\n  <li>ahead normally</li>\n  <li>at an angle</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You must also prove to the examiner that you can safely:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>meet other vehicles</li>\n  <li>overtake</li>\n  <li>cross the path of other vehicles</li>\n  <li>keep a safe separation distance</li>\n  <li>handle various types of roundabouts</li>\n  <li>exercise correct lane discipline</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You must show that you:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>can use all mirrors effectively</li>\n  <li>use all signals correctly</li>\n  <li>have alertness and anticipation</li>\n  <li>can obey speed limits</li>\n  <li>are aware of how the vehicle is running</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Independent driving</h3>\n\n<p>You’ll have to drive without turn-by-turn directions from the examiner for around 10 minutes. You’ll have to follow either:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>traffic signs</li>\n  <li>a series of directions given to you before you set off</li>\n  <li>a combination of both</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Off-road exercises</h3>\n\n<p>You must safely complete an off-road reversing exercise at the driving test centre, and an uncoupling and recoupling exercise if you want to instruct drivers of C1+E and C+E vehicles.</p>\n\n<h2>Your test result</h2>\n\n<p>The examiner will give you the result at the end of the test.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You’ll pass the driving ability test if you make 6 driving faults or less.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>You’ll fail if you make a serious or dangerous fault, or make more than 6 riding faults.</p>\n\n<h3>Failing the first or second attempt</h3>\n\n<p>You can take the test again if you fail the test at either your first or second attempt.</p>\n\n<h3>Failing the third attempt</h3>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>You have to retake and pass the <a href=\"/become-an-lgv-driving-instructor/taking-the-theory-test\" title=\"Taking the theory test\">theory test</a> again if you fail the driving ability test 3 times.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>You have to wait 1 year from when you first passed the theory test before you can take it again.</p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/become-an-lgv-driving-instructor/taking-the-instructional-ability-test","slug":"taking-the-instructional-ability-test","order":7,"title":"Taking the instructional ability test","body":"<p>To book the instructional ability test, use the application form you’re given when you pass the driving ability test.</p>\n\n<p>It costs £142.80.</p>\n\n<h2>What to bring to your test</h2>\n\n<p>On the day, you’ll need to bring:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>both parts of your driving licence - the photocard and the paper counterpart</li>\n  <li>the pass letter from the driving ability test</li>\n  <li>a suitable vehicle</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You must take your signed driving licence and a valid passport if you have an old-style paper licence.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Rules for the vehicle you use</h2>\n\n<p>You must bring a large goods vehicle (LGV) that:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>is roadworthy and legal</li>\n  <li>is a category C1, C1+E, C or C+E vehicle (depending on the instructor certificate you want)</li>\n  <li>has normal performance for its type</li>\n  <li>is not carrying any goods or burden</li>\n  <li>is a right-hand drive</li>\n  <li>has a seat for a forward-facing passenger</li>\n  <li>has seatbelts fitted for the examiner&rsquo;s use</li>\n  <li>has external nearside and offside mirrors for use by the examiner during the test</li>\n  <li>displays &lsquo;L&rsquo; plates during the test</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>How the test works</h2>\n\n<p>The examiner will begin by explaining which of the <a href=\"/become-an-lgv-driving-instructor/preparing-for-your-tests\" title=\"Preparing for your test\">9 possible pre-set exercises</a> will be used.</p>\n\n<p>The examiner will play the role of one of the following types of pupil:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>someone learning to drive either a category C1 or C</li>\n  <li>someone learning to drive either a category C1+E or C+E</li>\n  <li>someone who has already failed LGV test and needs extra training</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The examiner will drive the vehicle and simulate faults. You should treat the examiner as though they are your pupil.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You can use lesson plans and training aids, and you can bring brief notes or subject headings along with you.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h3>What you have to do</h3>\n\n<p>During the test, you have to:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>tailor your instruction to the standard of the pupil and the time available</li>\n  <li>give your pupil a chance to show what you&rsquo;ve taught them and correct any faults</li>\n  <li>keep control of the lesson, be patient and tactful and encourage the pupil</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>What the examiner assesses</h3>\n\n<p>The examiner will assess you on:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>the method of your instruction and how clear, thorough and correct it is</li>\n  <li>how well you observe and correct the pupil&rsquo;s driving errors</li>\n  <li>your general manner and attitude when dealing with the pupil</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Your test result</h2>\n\n<p>The examiner will give you the result at the end of the test.</p>\n\n<h3>Failing the first or second attempt</h3>\n\n<p>You can take the test again if you fail the test at either your first or second attempt.</p>\n\n<h3>Failing the third attempt</h3>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>You have to retake and pass the <a href=\"/become-an-lgv-driving-instructor/taking-the-theory-test\" title=\"Taking the theory test\">theory test</a> and <a href=\"/become-an-lgv-driving-instructor/taking-the-driving-ability-test\" title=\"Taking the driving ability test\">driving ability test</a> again if you fail the instructional ability test 3 times.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>You have to wait 1 year from when you first passed the theory test before you can take it again.</p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/become-an-lgv-driving-instructor/managing-your-registration","slug":"managing-your-registration","order":8,"title":"Managing your registration","body":"<p>Your name will be added to the large goods vehicle instructor (<abbr title=\"Large goods vehicle\">LGV</abbr>) register when you&rsquo;ve passed the 3 qualifying tests and paid the registration fee of £120.</p>\n\n<p>You&rsquo;ll then be sent your registration certificate, which lasts for 4 years.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You should display your certificate of registration in the bottom left-hand corner of the front windscreen of the vehicle when you’re giving instruction.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Staying on the register</h2>\n\n<p>You have to retake and pass the <a href=\"taking-the-driving-ability-test\" title=\"Taking the driving ability test\">driving ability test</a> and <a href=\"/become-an-lgv-driving-instructor/taking-the-instructional-ability-test\" title=\"Taking the instructional ability test\">instructional ability test</a> during the last 12 months of your r